'''Chemoproteomics''' is an approach to discovering mechanisms for regulating [[Biological pathway|biological pathways]] for the purpose of designing new pharmaceutical therapies. It is a chemical proteomic method for [[pharmacology|pharmacological discovery]] research.
==Introduction==
Chemoproteomics can enable [[drug discovery]].<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Raymond E. Moellering |author2=Benjamin F. Cravatt* | title = How chemoproteomics can enable drug discovery and development | journal = Chem. Biol. | volume = 19 | issue = 1 | pages = 11–22 | year = 2012 | doi = 10.1016/j.chembiol.2012.01.001 | pmid=22284350 | pmc=3312051}}</ref> It is a method for identifying protein targets and potential off-target activity.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.tdi.ox.ac.uk/dphil-projects/project/target-profiling-of-drugs-by-chemical-proteomics| title= Target Profiling of Drugs by Chemical Proteomics| website= Target Discovery Institute - TDI| accessdate= 4 Jan 2016| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160301024133/http://www.tdi.ox.ac.uk/dphil-projects/project/target-profiling-of-drugs-by-chemical-proteomics#| archive-date= 2016-03-01| dead-url= yes| df= }}</ref>
==Method== A linker molecule connects a small molecule chemical probe (or library of chemical probes) with an analytically detectable bead or other agent for detection or separation.<ref>{{cite journal| url = http://www.malariajournal.com/content/pdf/1475-2875-13-S1-P38.pdf | title = Identification of Plasmodium PI4 kinase as target of MMV390048 by chemoproteomics | journal = Malaria Journal | year = 2014 | author = Sonja Ghidelli-Disse1, Maria Jose Lafuente-Monasterio, David Waterson, Michael Witty, Yassir Younis, Tanya Paquet, Leslie J Street| doi = 10.1186/1475-2875-13-S1-P38|display-authors=etal | volume=13 | pages=P38}}</ref>
